be a solution. Also, I need to think about how metadata is managed for anonymous constructors in a native image context. It seems like I need to check how the agent works with metadata generation to ensure everything runs smoothly.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Examining privileges and security**\\n\\nI'm questioning whether I can directly instantiate `java.security.AccessController.doPrivileged`. Creating an instance of `SecurityActions$1`, an anonymous class, seems okay if I avoid `$` in the test file name. The rule mentions no dollar signs in test class names—perhaps I should refine the approach. If I use MethodHandles for running the `PrivilegedAction`, I might not need to tweak the security manager in Gradle. I'm considering reverting changes in `build.gradle` to focus solely on necessary adjustments.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_s2rORgF3WvF5oYGWWRsgk2qo|fc_0eeeed81a892fbb40169f12062e9e881a38029038449618f01", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "javap -classpath ~/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/javassist/javassist/3.12.0.GA/*/javassist-3.12.0.GA.jar -p 'javassist.util.proxy.SecurityActions$1' 2>/dev/null || find ~/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/javassist/javassist/3.12.0.GA -name '*.jar' -print", "timeout": 30}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 947, "output": 1023, "cacheRead": 60416, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 62386, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777410130296, "responseId": "resp_0eeeed81a892fbb40169f12052e90081a3ac8db07a07537a19"}}
